.Dd 2026-07-20
.Dt XXED 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm xxed
.Nd simple interactive hex editor
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl b Ar blocksize
.Ar file
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
opens
.Ar file
read/write and presents an interactive
.Li >
prompt.
Commands may be abbreviated to a single letter where unambiguous.
Entering a blank line repeats the most recent command.
.Sh COMMANDS
The following commands are available.
.Bl -tag -width "seek [+-]offset" -compact
.It Ic exit , quit , q
Exit
.Nm .
.It Ic echo Op Ar arg ...
Print the arguments separated by single spaces and a trailing newline.
.It Ic p , print
Print the next 16 lines (256 bytes maximum) starting at the current file
position, as: 8-digit hex offset, 16 hex bytes (with an extra space after the
8th byte), padding, a
.Li " | "
separator, then the ASCII representation with non-printable bytes shown as
.Sq \&.
.Pq a literal full stop .
The file position advances by the number of bytes read.
.It Ic s , seek Op Ar offset
Seek to
.Ar offset .
With no argument, seek to the start of the file.
A
.Sq +
or
.Sq -
prefix makes the seek relative to the current position; otherwise it is
absolute.
The new offset (hex) and block number are printed.
.El
.Pp
.Ar offset
is parsed by
.Xr strtoll 3
with base 0 (so a leading
.Li 0x
means hex) and may carry one of the following unit suffixes:
.Bl -tag -width "g , G" -compact
.It Sy b
block (multiplied by
.Ar blocksize )
.It Sy w
word (\(mu 2)
.It Sy d
doubleword (\(mu 4)
.It Sy q
quadword (\(mu 8)
.It Sy s
sector (\(mu 512)
.It Sy k , K
kibibyte (\(mu 1024)
.It Sy m , M
mebibyte (\(mu 1024^2)
.It Sy g , G
gibibyte (\(mu 1024^3)
.El
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl b Ar blocksize
Block size used as the multiplier for the
.Sy b
size suffix in the
.Ic seek
command.
Defaults to 512.
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh EXAMPLES
Inspect a binary using 2 KiB blocks:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ xxed -b 2048 firmware.bin
> p
> seek +0x200
> q
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr hexdump 1 ,
.Xr xxd 1 ,
.Xr od 1
